## Context
BGE-M3 may encode 1990s text less faithfully than 2020s text,
inflating early-year distributional distances. If break dates
change with a different embedding model, they reflect encoding
quality, not field structure.

## Actions
1. Choose second model. Candidates:
   - SPECTER2 (scientific papers, trained on citation graph)
   - all-MiniLM-L6-v2 (general, 384d, very different from BGE-M3)
   - Prefer one that's architecturally different from BGE-M3.
2. Embed a stratified sample (~5000 papers, ~250/decade) with
   both BGE-M3 and the alternative. Or embed full corpus if
   compute allows (full re-embed ~16 min on A4000).
3. Run corrected S1-S4 (ticket 0045) on both embedding sets.
4. Compare break dates. If same years survive → model-independent.
   If different → the breaks depend on embedding fine structure.

## Test
```python
def test_alternative_embeddings_same_shape():
    """Both models produce same number of rows, aligned with works."""
```

## Exit criteria
Comparison table: break year × model. Paper states whether
periodization is embedding-model-dependent or not.

## Compute estimate
Full re-embed: ~16 min GPU. S1-S4 run: ~3.5 min. Total: ~20 min.
